design_description: 100-200ng of whole blood-derived DNA was fragmented under mild settings using a low volume AFA plate on the Covaris LE220 to target 500bp fragments in accordance with manufacturer's instructions. Fragmented samples were then processed with the KAPA Hyper Library Preparation kit (Roche) following the manufacturer's recommendations.

100-200ng of FFPE-DNA was fragmented under mild settings using a low volume AFA plate on the Covaris LE220 to target 500bp fragments in accordance with manufacturer's instructions. Fragmented samples were then processed with the KAPA Hyper Library Preparation kit (Roche) following the modifications for degraded samples.

Approximately 800ng of RNA were used to prepare libraries using a Illumina Stranded Total RNA Prep with RiboZero Gold and bar-coded with individual tags following the manufacturer instructions. Samples were then pooled into batches of 32-92 and sequenced on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000, paired end 50 base pairs to generate a minimum of 150 million reads per sample library with a target of greater than 90% mapped reads.

miRNA-seq library construction used the NEXTflex Small RNA-Seq Kit (v3, PerkinElmer, Waltham, MA) prepared on a Sciclone Liquid Handling Workstation. Pooled libraries were then size selected according to NEXTflex Kit specifications using a Pippin Prep system (Sage Science, Beverly, MA). Pools of approximately 20 were sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 to generate a minimum of approximately 10 million reads per library. Samples that did not reach coverage were sequenced a second time. A subset of cases have two FASTQ files that should be analyzed together.

miRNA-seq library construction used the NEXTflex Small RNA-Seq Kit (v3, PerkinElmer, Waltham, MA) prepared on a Sciclone Liquid Handling Workstation. Pooled libraries were then size selected according to NEXTflex Kit specifications using a Pippin Prep system (Sage Science, Beverly, MA). Pools of approximately 20 were sequenced on an Illumina HiSeq 4000 to generate a minimum of approximately 10 million reads per library. Samples that did not reach coverage were sequenced a second time. A subset of cases have two FASTQ files that should be analyzed together.
